[[File:USSR Republics Numbered Alphabetically.png|upright=1.6|thumb|Post-Soviet states in English alphabetical order: {{flatlist|{{ordered list|[[Armenia]]|[[Azerbaijan]]|[[Belarus]]|[[Estonia]]|[[Georgia (country)|Georgia]]|[[Kazakhstan]]|[[Kyrgyzstan]]|[[Latvia]]|[[Lithuania]]|[[Moldova]]|[[Russia]]|[[Tajikistan]]|[[Turkmenistan]]|[[Ukraine]]|[[Uzbekistan]]}}}}]]
The '''post-Soviet states''', also collectively known as the '''former Soviet Union''' ('''FSU''')<ref>{{cite web|url=http://belfercenter.ksg.harvard.edu/publication/1805/managing_conflict_in_the_former_soviet_union.html|title=Managing Conflict in the Former Soviet Union: Russian and American Perspectives|date=30 October 1997|work=harvard.edu|accessdate=2 December 2015}}</ref> or '''former Soviet Republics''', and in Russian as the "'''near abroad'''" (discussed below) are the [[Sovereign state|states]] that emerged and re-emerged from the [[Soviet Union|Union of Soviet Socialist Republics]] in its [[dissolution of the Soviet Union|breakup]] in 1991, with [[Russia]] internationally recognised as the [[Succession of states|successor state]] to the Soviet Union after the [[Cold War]]. The three [[Baltic states]] were the first to declare their independence, between March and May 1990, claiming [[State continuity of the Baltic states|continuity from the original states]] that existed prior to their annexation by the Soviet Union in 1940.<ref name="Elsuwege">{{cite book|last=Van Elsuwege|first=Peter|title=From Soviet Republics to Eu Member States: A Legal and Political Assessment of the Baltic States' Accession to the EU|series=Studies in EU External Relations|volume=1|year=2008|publisher=BRILL|isbn=9789004169456|page=xxii}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=Estonia |last=Smith |first=David James |authorlink= |coauthors= |year=2001 |publisher=Routledge |location= |isbn=0-415-26728-5 |page=20 |pages= |url=https://books.google.com/?id=lx-UmTnLJv0C&pg=PR20&dq}}</ref>  The remaining 12 republics all subsequently seceded.<ref name="Elsuwege"/> 12 of the 15 states, excluding the Baltic states, initially formed the [[Commonwealth of Independent States|CIS]] and most joined [[Collective Security Treaty Organization|CSTO]], while the Baltic states focused on [[European Union]] and [[NATO]] membership.

Several [[List of states with limited recognition|disputed states with varying degrees of recognition]] exist within the territory of the former Soviet Union: [[Transnistria]] in eastern [[Moldova]], [[Abkhazia]] and [[South Ossetia]] in northern [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]] and [[Nagorno-Karabakh]] in southwestern [[Azerbaijan]]. Since 2014, the [[Donetsk People's Republic]] and [[Luhansk People's Republic]] in [[Eastern Ukraine]] have claimed independence. All of these unrecognised states except Nagorno-Karabakh depend on Russian armed support and financial aid. Nagorno-Karabakh is integrated to [[Armenia]], which also maintains close cooperation with [[Russia]]. Prior to the [[Annexation of Crimea to the Russian Federation|annexation of Crimea]] to Russia in March 2014, which is not recognized by most countries, it briefly declared itself an independent state.

In the political language of [[Russia]] and some other post-Soviet states, the '''near abroad''' refers to the newly independent republics (other than Russia itself) which emerged after the [[dissolution of the Soviet Union]]. "'''Near abroad'''" became more widely used in [[English language|English]], usually to assert Russia's right to have major influence in the region,<ref name=nyt>{{cite web|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9C07EED81E39F931A15756C0A962958260|title= ON LANGUAGE; The Near Abroad|accessdate=2008-04-18|author=[[William Safire]]|date=1994-05-22|work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/02/05/AR2008020502879.html|title=New Europe, Old Russia|accessdate=2008-04-18|author=[[Robert Kagan]]|date=2008-02-06|work=[[The Washington Post]]}}</ref><ref name=se01/> but also for marketing purposes by various companies.{{cn|date=September 2014}} [[President of Russia|Russian President]] [[Vladimir Putin]] has declared the region Russia's "[[sphere of influence]]", and strategically vital for Russia.<ref name=se01>{{cite web|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9A05E5D91039F936A15751C0A9679C8B63|title=The World; Learning to Fear Putin's Gaze|accessdate=2008-04-18|author=[[Steven Erlanger]]|date=2001-02-25|work=New York Times}}</ref> The concept has been compared to the [[Monroe Doctrine]].<ref name=nyt/>

==Country comparison==
===States and geographical groupings===
[[File:PostSoviet Regions Map.png|upright=1.15|thumb|right|Common groupings of the post-Soviet states:<br>
{{legend|#0065c8|[[Baltic states]]}}
{{legend|#688856|[[Central Asia]]}}
{{legend|#ffc600|[[Eastern Europe]]}}
{{legend|#f2553e|[[Russia]]}}
{{legend|#f18cbf|[[Transcaucasia]]}}]]

The 15 post-Soviet states are typically divided into the following five groupings. Each of these regions has its own common set of traits, owing not only to geographic and cultural factors but also to that region's history in relation to [[Russia]]. In addition, there are a number of de facto independent, but internationally unrecognized states (see the section [[#Separatist conflicts|Separatist conflicts]] below).

