{{Multiple issues| {{Advert|date=November 2016}} {{COI|date=November 2016}} }} {{Use dmy dates|date=July 2017}} {{Infobox recurring event | name = RideLondon | logo = RideLondon logo.png | status = Active | genre = | frequency = Annually | venue = | location = | coordinates = <!-- {{coord|LAT|LON|type:event|display=inline,title}} --> | country = United Kingdom | years_active = <!-- {{age|YYYY|mm|dd}} Date of the first occurrence --> | first = 2013 | founder_name = [[Mayor of London]], [[London and Partners]], [[Transport for London]] and [[Surrey County Council]] | last = <!-- Date of most recent event; if the event will not be held again, use {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD|df=y}} --> | prev = | next = 28–29 July 2018 | participants = | attendance = | capacity = | area = | budget = | activity = Cycling | leader_name = | patron = | organised = London & Surrey Cycling Partnership | filing = | people = | member = | sponsor = [[Prudential plc]] | website = {{URL|https://www.ridelondon.co.uk/}} | footnotes = }}
''' RideLondon''', known through sponsorship as '''Prudential RideLondon''', is an annual festival of cycling held in [[London]]. It was developed by the [[Mayor of London]], [[London and Partners]] and [[Transport for London]] in partnership with [[Surrey County Council]], and is managed by London & Surrey Cycling Partnership.{{citation needed|date=July 2018}}
The festival was designed as an annual legacy from the London 2012 Olympic Games and first held in 2013. The format consists of a series of cycling events on closed roads around London and [[Surrey]] for amateur [[cyclist]]s and professionals, culminating in the [[London–Surrey Classic]], a one-day international [[road cycling]].{{citation needed|date=July 2018}}
==Overview== Prudential RideLondon is composed of a number of events taking place the weekend following the end of the Tour de France at the end of July every year.{{citation needed|date=July 2018}}
===Prudential RideLondon FreeCycle=== Taking place on the Saturday, the Prudential RideLondon FreeCycle offers an opportunity for people of all ages to cycle on traffic-free roads in Central London, passing landmarks such as [[Buckingham Palace]], the [[Bank of England]], the [[Houses of Parliament]] and [[St Paul's Cathedral]]. Alongside the FreeCycle route, there are also seven festival zones, all of which have a variety of bike-based activates riders can get involved in.{{citation needed|date=July 2018}}
===Prudential RideLondon Classique=== The Prudential RideLondon Classique is a [[UCI Women's WorldTour]] race on the Saturday evening on a 5.5&nbsp;km circuit in central London, beginning and finishing on [[The Mall, London|The Mall]]. The women’s elite race, previously known as the Grand Prix pro race, was given UCI World Tour Status in 2016 and has the highest ever value prize money for a women’s one-day race. This is also the same prize money as won in the men’s elite race, despite the lessened interest.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.prudentialridelondon.co.uk/events/classique/prizes/prize-money/|title=Prize Money|website=www.prudentialridelondon.co.uk|access-date=2018-10-21}}</ref>
===Prudential RideLondon-Surrey 100=== The Prudential RideLondon-Surrey 100 takes place on the Sunday. Over 25,000 amateur cyclists start in Queen Elizabeth Olympic Park, then cycle through the capital and onto Surrey's country roads and the [[Surrey Hills AONB|Surrey Hills]] before a finish on The Mall in central London. Many of the riders are sponsored for charities: £12.5 million was raised for charity in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.londonandpartners.com/media-centre/press-releases/2016/20160120prudential-ridelondon-raises-recordbreaking-12-million-for-charity|title=Prudential Ridelondon raises record-breaking £12 million for charity|website=www.londonandpartners.com|accessdate=30 July 2017}}</ref>
===Prudential RideLondon-Surrey 46=== First established in 2016, the Prudential RideLondon-Surrey 46 takes place on the Sunday morning. The 46-mile route on traffic-free roads begins at [[Queen Elizabeth Olympic Park]] in east London and follows the same route as the Prudential RideLondon-Surrey 100 for the first 27 miles before linking to with the last 17 miles through London to the finish in The Mall.{{citation needed|date=July 2018}}
===Prudential RideLondon-Surrey Classic=== The Prudential RideLondon-Surrey Classic on the Sunday, is a UCI WorldTour event which follows largely the same route as the Prudential RideLondon-Surrey 100 sportive with multiple circuits in and around [[Dorking]].{{citation needed|date=July 2018}}
===Brompton World Championship=== The [[Brompton World Championship]] first became part of the RideLondon cycling festival in 2015. The event involves 550 Brompton riders racing around a central London circuit on the iconic foldable bikes and ends with a sprint finish on The Mall. Riders are generally dressed in suits, due to the strict no lycra rule in order to reflect the Brompton bikes place in a modern-day commuter lifestyle.{{citation needed|date=July 2018}}
===Prudential RideLondon HandCycle Races and Junior Races=== The prudential RideLondon HandCycle and Junior races are also included in the RideLondon weekend. The elite HandCycle event has been won by Rafal Wilk of Poland in 2016 and 2017 while Christine Reppe of Germany won the women’s elite handcycle in 2017. The amateur handcycle event is for injured veteran servicemen and women. The Junior categories feature boys and girls races for 13–16 years old. {{citation needed|date=July 2018}}
==History==
===Origins=== The origins of RideLondon can be traced back to when London was awarded the rights to stage the 2012 [[Olympic Games|Olympic]] & [[Paralympic Games]]. Subsequently, London has staged a number of cycling events. In 2007, London hosted the [[Tour de France]] Grand Depart and also closed roads to create a day-long safe cycling environment in city centre, known at the time as [[The London Freewheel]]. This annual one day event continued between 2007-2011 and from 2009 became known as the Mayor of London's Skyride.{{citation needed|date=July 2018}}
Ambition to create a new world-class event for cycling, that could one day rival London's most iconic sporting events such as the [[London Marathon]] and the [[Wimbledon Championships]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/a36d44fe-cc0b-11e1-aac1-00144feabdc0|title=Subscribe to read|website=Financial Times|accessdate=30 July 2017}}</ref> was born. The aim of the annual event is to include the world's top men, women and hand cyclists racing as part of the international cycling calendar in order to challenge and inspire people from all backgrounds to get on two wheels. In late 2011 and early 2012, Mayor [[Boris Johnson]] assessed and formally approved the recommendation to create the event <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.london.gov.uk/press-releases-4850|title=Mayor announces world class cycling festival|website=London City Hall|accessdate=30 July 2017}}</ref> and, at the start of the Olympic year, the search for a suitably qualified and experienced Delivery Partner was launched.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.london.gov.uk/press-releases-4788|title=Six race organisers shortlisted to run London Festival of Cycling|website=London City Hall|accessdate=30 July 2017}}</ref> After detailed work, a joint venture including the organisers of London Marathon and the [[Tour of Britain]] under the name of the London & Surrey Cycling Partnership was selected to make the event a reality. The event would be delivered in partnership with [[Surrey County Council]] and include a route through the Surrey Hills, which also mirrored the London Olympic Games road race. The event is part of the London 2012 Olympic legacy.
In August 2012, as the Olympic Games drew to a close, the Mayor of London and the London & Surrey Cycling Partnership, alongside British Cycling and double Olympic champion [[Laura Kenny|Laura Trott]], formally launched RideLondon <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.london.gov.uk/press-releases-4616|title=Mayor announces world class RideLondon event|website=London City Hall|accessdate=30 July 2017}}</ref> and called for fans to sign up to the 100-mile challenge. The event's first title sponsor, Prudential, was announced in early 2013 <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.londonandpartners.com/media-centre/press-releases/2013/130207-prudential-to-sponsor-mayors-ridelondon-festival-of-cycling|title=Prudential to sponsor Mayor's RideLondon Festival of Cycling|website=www.londonandpartners.com|accessdate=30 July 2017}}</ref> by which time more than 55,000 people had signed up to be one of the first riders to participate in the inaugural RideLondon-Surrey 100. This race is part of the Prudential RideLondon festival weekend with coverage to be broadcast live on [[BBC]] and international TV.
The RideLondon vision was to showcase the capital to nationwide and international audiences, generate economic benefit from participant and spectator expenditure and inspire more people to take up regular cycling.{{citation needed|date=July 2018}}
===2013 Event=== In its first year, more than 16,000 people started the RideLondon-Surrey 100, more than 50,000 took part in RideLondon FreeCycle and over 1,000 volunteers helped run the event. 99% of participants rated the event as good or excellent and riders in the RideLondon-Surrey 100 raised more than £7 million for charity.<ref>http://www.londonandpartners.com/media-centre/press-releases/2014/140807-sir-bradley-wiggins-to-race-in-prudential-ridelondonsurrey-classic</ref>
===2014 Event=== In 2014, over 16,000 completed the RideLondon-Surrey 100 (shortened to 86 miles due to adverse weather conditions) with 60,000 taking part in the FreeCycle <ref>http://www.londonandpartners.com/media-centre/press-releases/2014/140811-a-fantastic-advert-for-cycling-says-mayor-boris-johnson</ref> and more than £10 million being raised for charity by riders in the RideLondon-Surrey 100. This set a new record for a UK one-day cycling event for a second successive year.
===2015 Event=== In response to the huge demand for the event, places were increased by 25 per cent in 2015, with more than 25,000 riders crossing the Start Line in Queen Elizabeth Park Olympic Park on 2 August.<ref>http://www.londonandpartners.com/media-centre/press-releases/2015/150803-mayor-boris-johnson-hails-the-worlds-greatest-cycling-festival</ref> This year a new event was also added to the RideLondon cycling festival; the 10th Brompton Bicycle World Championship Final. This event which featured in the RideLondon Grand Prix races in St James's Park and was the first time that the Brompton World Championship Final had been held in London. The event opened with a Le Mans-style start as 500 smartly-dressed competitors from around the world made a mad dash to unfold their bikes before setting off on the circuit. Six Festival Zones (up from five in 2014) in RideLondon FreeCycle offered riders a chance to stop and enjoy a huge range of free bike-based entertainment and to try out many different bike-based activities. The women's RideLondon Grand Prix race was also one of the biggest one-day races on the international calendar and was again televised live by the BBC.{{citation needed|date=July 2018}}
===2016 Event=== In 2016, a new 46 mile event was launched by Bradley Wiggins specifically for newer and younger cyclists. The RideLondon-Surrey 46 on traffic-free roads starts at Queen Elizabeth Olympic Park, and follows the same route as RideLondon-Surrey 100 for the first 27 miles before taking a new two-mile route, which then links up with the last 17 miles to the finish in The Mall.{{citation needed|date=July 2018}}
A new format for the RideLondon Grand Prix was also announced. From 2016 it is to be held at the Lee Valley Velopark in Queen Elizabeth Olympic Park and include handcycle, junior and BMX races for the first time.{{citation needed|date=July 2018}}
===2017 Event=== In 2017, the RideLondon-Surrey Classic and RideLondon Classique both gained UCI WorldTour status and became the richest one-day races in cycling offering equal prize money for both the men's and women's races.<ref>https://www.prudentialridelondon.co.uk/news-media/latest-news/2017-prudential-ridelondon-surrey-classic-makes-history/</ref> Riders in the RideLondon-Surrey 100 and RideLondon-Surrey 46 together raised £12.75 million for charity.<ref>http://www.londonandpartners.com/media-centre/press-releases/2017/181217-ridelondon-cyclists-raise-127-million-for-charity-in-2017</ref>
