'''Zarir''' (also spelled '''Zarih''') was a [[Sasanian]] prince who was the leader of a rebellion in northern [[Sasanian Empire|Iran]] in 485.

According to [[Armenians|Armenian]] historian [[Ghazar Parpetsi]], who is the only source about the life of Zarir, the latter was a son of the Sasanian [[shah]] [[Yazdegerd II]]. He had several brothers named [[Balash]], [[Hormizd III]], and [[Peroz I]]. After the death of Peroz I (who had succeeded his father as king), Balash was elected as king by the nobility and clergy. Zarir, dissatisfied with the election, rebelled. Balash was thus forced to make peace with his enemy [[Vahan Mamikonian]] and sent him at the head of an army to suppress the rebellion of Zarir. Zarir was shortly defeated, and fled to the mountains, but was quickly captured and "shot down like an animal".

